                       <tr> 
                        <td height="63"><img src="../global/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="1"> 
                           <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td bgcolor="#000000" height="8" width="100%" colspan="3"><span class="header">Dilemma Combos 103</span></td></tr><tr><td bgcolor="#333399" height="2" width="41%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="1%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="58%" bgcolor="#FF9C00"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td></tr></table><TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN=2><SPAN CLASS="header">Rating </SPAN><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/rating/9.gif" BORDER=0></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=11"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=11"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=1680">Matt "Figrin" Kirk</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Description</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%"><span class=text>Third in the series, this article examines specific dilemmas in combination, and suggests ways to improve combinations for increased effectiveness.</span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Article</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%" ><span class=text>DISCLAIMER: This article is intended for less experienced players of STCCG. More experienced players should read my 200 series on Dilemma Combos.<br>
<br>
In the past two articles, I&#146;ve discussed effective ways to create dilemma &quot;combos&quot;; that is, a set of 2-5 dilemmas, all meant to be seeded underneath a specific mission in a predetermined order, preferably with early effects that amplify the later ones. Let&#146;s start with a simple example; all cards will taken taken from Premiere, and as we discuss ways to improve the combo, I&#146;ll add in cards from other expansions. I&#146;ll also add a substitution suggestion or two, should you not actually have the card listed (this is for those of you who asked for a &quot;rareless&quot; option). Here&#146;s what we&#146;re starting with:<br>
<br>
Combo set 1A:<br>
Anaphasic Organism(C), Female&#146;s Love Interest(C), Matriarchal Society(U).<br>
<br>
Using the filter-killer-wall handles, let&#146;s define each of these:<br>
<br>
Anaphasic Organism [KILLER] &quot;If females in Away Team (AT), the one with highest total attributes resigns (discarded), unless SECURITY and MEDICAL present. Discard dilemma.&quot;<br>
Female&#146;s Love Interest [FILTER] &quot;Female AT member (random selection) runs off with lover to furthest planet. Can be rescued later. Discard dilemma.&quot;<br>
Matriarchal Society [WALL] &quot;Cannot get past unless at least 2 female AT members present.&quot;<br>
<br>
This combo&#146;s purpose is clear enough; eliminate at least 1, possibly 2 females, and require the opponent to have 2 more. However, as the combo stands right now, it is not at peak effectiveness. By placing the Love Interest ahead of the Organism, you increase the chances of filtering out the SECURITY or MEDICAL needed to pass the Organism. So our improved version looks like this:<br>
<br>
Combo set 1B:<br>
Female&#146;s Love Interest(C)[F]<br>
Anaphasic Organism(C)[K]<br>
Matriarchal Society(U)[W]<br>
<br>
So the effects now will stack something like this; randomly remove a female (hopefully who has either SEC or MED), then kill the female with highest attributes unles SEC + MED present, then you still need 2 more females to get past. This combo is as good as it&#146;s going to get at this point.<br>
<br>
Having said that, we now run into the problem of red-shirting. Red-shirting is a shorthand term meaning the sacrifice of a single hapless personnel to clear all bad and nasty dilemmas before the mission solvers come in (you will understand the reference if you have ever seen the original Star Trek series... if not, watch GalaxyQuest. Guy - Crewman #6 is the quintessential red-shirt. He&#146;s wearing blue, but in original ST, characters like his wore red.) If a single male personnel were to beam down and attempt this mission, he would avoid the ill effects of both the first and second dilemmas, and simply run into the wall. This presents a problem. How do you make sure your opponent attempts with personnel for your dilemmas to pick off?<br>
<br>
The current (Feb 2001) metagame (at least in my area) being what it is, red-shirting is not nearly as popular as it used to be, for the simple fact that there are many dilemmas now that severely punish red-shirt attempts. Metagame is another term you may not be familiar with. Literally meaning &quot;the game beyond the game&quot;, a region&#146;s metagame is usually the deciding factor for the inclusion of certain cards within a deck. For instance, if your area has many people using Rogue Borg Mercenaries, you may want to include cards like Hugh, Borg Neuroprocessor, or Reactor Overload in your deck. This is an example of playing an given players&#146; group&#146;s metagame. The usage of counter-strategies dependant upon the current play environment.<br>
<br>
Back to red-shirting; if it doesn&#146;t happen all that often in your area, then this combo should work just fine. However, if the opposite is true, this combo will not hold up very well. In this case, the wall-filter-killer type of combo is usually more effective. Let&#146;s examine this combo if we were to rearrange the order of the combo to W/F/K:<br>
<br>
Combo set 1C:<br>
Matriarchal Society(U)[W]<br>
Female&#146;s Love Interest(C)[F]<br>
Anaphasic Organism(C)[K]<br>
<br>
Not the best, but the order ensures that a female will be present to be whisked away by the Love Interest. So after the Society is cleared, the rest of the combo is not all that effective (except for the aforementioned guaranteed female). There is a single dilemma that can be added to any combo to immediately ensure that your opponent will have to attempt the mission with at least enough personnel to meet the mission requirements (as long as they&#146;re not playing Borg, in which case this combo is not effective at all). The first of many anti-redshirt dilemmas: Lack of Preparation. This was really the first dilemma to severely punish a player for redshirting (unless, of course, the mission only required one personnel to complete). Added to the front of 1B, we get:<br>
<br>
Combo set 1D:<br>
Lack of Preparation(C)[W] &quot;Non-Borg: Cannot get past (lose 10 points) unless you could have met mission requirements at start of attempt.&quot;<br>
Female&#146;s Love Interest(C)[F]<br>
Anaphasic Organism(C)[K]<br>
Matriarchal Society(U)[W]<br>
<br>
In my experience I have found the most efficient amount of dilemmas in a seed deck is 18; 3 dilemmas for each of the opponent&#146;s 6 missions. This allows 12 seed slots for other seeded &quot;essentials&quot; like Q&#146;s Tent, Assign Mission Specialists, etc. If you&#146;ve seeded everything else, and still have seed slots you have no idea what to do with, when in doubt, seed more dilemmas! Opponents never like seeing 4 or even 5 dilemmas under a single mission. This combo has grown to 4 cards, but its effectiveness has also dramatically increased. Depending on where you seed this combo, Ferengi Infestation may be a better choice, since the opponent may have to commit even more personnel than he normally would to complete the mission. <br>
<br>
In Dilemma Combos 104, I&#146;ll continue examining specific combos and ways to improve them. I hope I&#146;ve successfully demonstrated my thought process when creating combos (even if at an elementary level). Any requests for the next segemnt? Dmail me, and I&#146;ll see if I can&#146;t squeeze it into 104. Thanks for reading. </span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=11"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=11"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="/stccg/global/images/back.gif" border="0" ></a></TD><TD><a href="articleprint.php3?article=11" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="/stccg/global/images/print.gif" border="0"></a></TD></TR></TABLE>
                        </td>
                      </tr>
